ed accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis anthology brings together the late Barry A. Crouch's most important articles on the African American experience in Texas during Reconstruction. Grouped topically, the essays explore what freedom meant to the newly emancipated, how white Texans reacted to the freed slaves, and how Freedmen's Bureau agents and African American politicians worked to improve the lot of ordinary African American Texans. The volume also contains Crouch's seminal review of Reconstruction historiography, "Unmanacling Texas Reconstruction: A Twenty-Year Perspective." The introductory pieces by Arnoldo De Leon and Larry Madaras recapitulate Barry Crouch's scholarly career and pay tribute to his stature in the field of Reconstruction history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightszTexasxHistoryy19th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszTexasxHistoryy19th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszTexasxPolitics and governmenty19th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszTexasxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aFreedmenzTexasxHistoryy19th century. 0aRacismzTexasxHistoryy19th century. 0aReconstruction (U.S. history, 1865-1877)zTexas. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh1 aCrouch, Barry A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe León, Arnoldo.1 aMadaras, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadaras, Larry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchultz, L. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71463240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292795570423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292795570/original  aEBA_BACKALL